@benoit-pierre I'm basically fine with all that, but I don't really know how to turn that patch into a commit. Can you just push it to my branch?

The big thing I still disagree with is xfail tests, but admittedly it's not a *big* problem (and to some extent it's actually a bit weird in setuptools because many xfail tests actually only fail on a specific platform). I think the best way to articulate how I feel about `xfail` tests is that they *aren't actual tests*. They're more like "TODO" list options because you don't actually test any behavior. The only guarantee you get out of an xfail is that the application *doesn't have the expected behavior*. You're not actually testing that it fails in any specific way, so the nature of the failure could change from version to version. Nothing that is *only* hit by a failing tests is *actually* covered, which is why I exclude them from coverage metrics.

With regards to them being a separate output, I actually like that, because when I run the test suite, I want to see all '......s....' for the covered portion and all 'xxxxxxx' in the un-covered portion.

> I would generally agree, other than the last one. The only reason tox -e coverage -- html is nicer to view for now is because we have a lot of lines of code untested (so the output gets a bit noisy). And doing that also forces the user to fire up a browser just to see what's happening thinking

@gaborbernat This may be true, but in a lot of libraries you have some paths that are only taken on one interpreter or the other, not both, so 100% coverage on each platform is not possible even if you can get 100% combined coverage. As such, you're *always* going to see a mess of lines on any one platform (unless we define some complicated per-platform coverage pragma, which would likely make the *code* messier).

