I got a little problem

In numpy_result_set.cpp we have this:
```
	if (not rows_in_batch)
	{
		throw pybind11::stop_iteration();
	}
```

This is problematic because there is no empty "typed" list being returned any longer, via 

```
	std::vector<std::unique_ptr<masked_column>> columns;
	for (std::size_t i = 0; i != n_columns; ++i) {
		columns.push_back(make_masked_column(column_info[i].type));
	}
```

so when we retrieve the result set, we don't get anything except a StopIteration exception. The reason why I have a problem with this, is that this differs in the previous behavior of returning empty **typed** arrays, which we cannot do any longer.

Should we
1) Not raise the stop iteration, initialise the empty list, and catch the fact that its empty in the python and modify the generator?
2) Not be concerned about this?
3) Do something else?

>either (a) leave out the include or (b) ask whether to remove the conflicting entries

@jsha I think option (a) would be better for usability, however, I'm worried that letsencrypt cloud retain (for example) an insecure cipher list.

> option that essentially says, "I have set up SSL but just want to use a cert from letsencrypt."

@diracdeltas could this be automated? letencrypt-nginx would only copy over `options-ssl-nginx.conf` if no SSL-enabled vhosts are found before installation.

